04826nam a22005895i 9781552384275DE-B159720240306010644.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||240306t20052005xxc    fo  d z      eng d  a97815523842757 a10.1515/97815523842752doi  a(DE-B1597)663869  a(OCoLC)1414456940  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  axxccCA 4aF551b.P47 2005eb 7aHIS0360002bisacsh04a9772221 aBukowczyk, John J., eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aPermeable Border :bThe Great Lakes Basin as Transnational Region, 1650-1990 /cNora Faires, David R. Smith, Randy W. Widdis, John J. Bukowczyk. 1aCalgary, Alberta : bUniversity of Calgary Press, c[2005] 4cÂ©2005  a1 online resource (312 p.) :b13 illustrations, 2 graphs, 11 maps, 5 tables, notes, further reading, bibliography, index  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFront Matter -- tContents -- tIllustrations -- tAcknowledgments -- tThe Production of History, the Becoming of Place -- tTrade, War, Migration, and Empire in the Great Lakes Basin, 1650-1815 -- tMigration, Transportation, Capital, and the State in the Great Lakes Basin, 1815-1890 -- tLeaving the "Land of the Second Chance" -- tStructuring the Permeable Border -- tMigration, Borderlands, and National Identity -- tRegion, Border, and Nation -- tPrimary Sources in Migration Studies -- tNotes -- tFor Further Reading -- tSelect Bibliography -- tContributors -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aFrom the colonial era of waterborne transport, through nineteenth-century changes in transportation and communication, to globalization, the history of the Great Lakes Basin has been shaped by the people, goods, and capital crossing and recrossing the U.S.-Canadian border. During the past three centuries, the region has been buffeted by efforts to benefit from or defeat economic and political integration and by the politics of imposing, tightening, or relaxing the bisecting international border. Where tariff policy was used in the early national period to open the border for agricultural goods, growing protectionism in both countries transformed the border into a bulwark against foreign competition after the 1860s. In the twentieth century, labour migration, followed by multinational corporations, fundamentally altered the customary pairing of capital and nation to that of capital versus nation, challenging the concept of international borders as key factors in national development. In tracing the economic development of the Great Lakes Basin as borderland and as transnational region, the authors of Permeable Border : The Great Lakes Basin as Transnational Region, 1650-1990 have provided a regional history that transcends national borders and makes vital connections between two national histories that are too often studied as wholly separate.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aTransnationalismxHistoryvCongresses. 7aHISTORY / United States / General.2bisacsh1 aBukowczyk, John J., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aFaires, Nora, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut1 aFaires, Nora, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aSmith, David R., eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut1 aSmith, David R., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aWiddis, Randy William, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertACUP Complete eBook-Package Pre-2010z978311127416408iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertACUP Upgrade eBook-Package pre 2010z978311127724040uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/9781552384275?locatt=mode:legacy40uhttps://www.degruyter.c